          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search            The Angel of Broadway   Directed by Lois Weber   Produced by Cecil B. DeMille   Written by John W. Krafft (intertitles)   Screenplay by Lenore J. Coffee   Story by Lenore J. Coffee   Starring Leatrice Joy   Cinematography Arthur C. Miller   Edited by Harold McLernon   Distributed by Pathé Exchange    Release dates     October 3, 1927 (1927-10-03) (United States)          Country United States   Language Silent English intertitles   The Angel of Broadway was a 1927 American silent drama film produced by Cecil B. DeMille and distributed by Pathé Exchange. It was directed by Lois Weber and starred Leatrice Joy. The film is now considered lost.[1][2][3] Cast[edit]  Leatrice Joy - Babe Scott Victor Varconi - Jerry Wilson May Robson - Big Bertha Alice Lake - Goldie Elise Bartlett - Gertie Ivan Lebedeff - Lonnie Jane Keckley - Captain Mary Clarence Burton - Herman Carmencita Johnson - Baby (uncredited) Rosina Lawrence - Dancer (uncredited)  References[edit]   ^ The Angel of Broadway at silentera.com ^ The Angel of Broadway at Arne Andersen's Lost Film Files:Pathe Exchange Films 1927 ^ The Library of Congress American Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: The Angel of Broadway   External links[edit]  The Angel of Broadway at the Internet Movie Database The Angel of Broadway at AllMovie          v t e   Films directed by Lois Weber          The Fine Feathers (1912)*short A Japanese Idyll (1912)*short Leaves in the Storm (1912)*short Suspense (1913)*short It's No Laughing Matter (1915) Hypocrites (1915) Sunshine Molly (1915) Captain Courtesy (1915) Where Are My Children? (1916) John Needham's Double (1916) Hop, The Devil's Brew (1916) Hand That Rocks the Cradle (1917) For Husbands Only (1917) What's Worth While? (1921) Too Wise Wives (1921) The Blot (1921) A Chapter in Her Life (1923) Sensation Seekers (1927) The Angel of Broadway (1934)             This 